            <div id="metadata" style="display: none;"><div data-category="settings" data-key="shell style" data-value-type="json">"boxed"</div><div data-category="main" data-key="header" data-value-type="html"></div></div>
            <div id="document"><h1>Algebra</h1>
<p>The Algebra Rule is a special built-in validation tool that Lurch provides for evaluating algebraic identities. It does not import any additional libraries.</p>
<div class="lurch-atom" data-metadata_type="&quot;rule&quot;" data-shell_title="Rule:">
<p><strong>Algebra.</strong>&nbsp; &nbsp;The <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expression&quot;" data-metadata_lurch-notation="&quot;AlgebraRule&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__text">algebra rule </span></span></span></span></span> uses a computer algebra system to evaluate algebraic identities (equations only) and also inequalities that are supported by the Arithmetic Rule for rational numbers.</p>
</div>
<p>If a the meaningful expression 'by algebra' follows a claim, Lurch will try to use the computer algebra system <a href="http://algebrite.org">Algebrite </a>to determine if the given claim is valid.&nbsp; The claim must be an equation. For example, it can check something like this:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;x^2-1=(x-1)\\cdot(x+1)&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__mathit">x</span><span class="ML__msubsup"><span class="ML__vlist-t"><span class="ML__vlist-r"><span class="ML__vlist" style="height: 0.87em;"><span style="top: -3.41em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span style="height: 0.46em; display: inline-block; font-size: 70%;"><span class="ML__cmr">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="ML__cmr">−</span><span class="ML__cmr">1</span><span class="ML__cmr">=</span><span class="ML__cmr">(</span><span class="ML__mathit">x</span><span class="ML__cmr">−</span><span class="ML__cmr">1)</span><span class="ML__cmr">⋅</span><span class="ML__cmr">(</span><span class="ML__mathit">x</span><span class="ML__cmr">+</span><span class="ML__cmr">1)</span></span></span></span></span> by algebra</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">It also will use the computer algebra system to check inequalities that are supported by the built-in validation tool for arithmetic over the rational numbers, namely ones that only involve the natural number constants <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;0,1,2,3,\\ldots&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">0,</span><span class="ML__cmr">1,</span><span class="ML__cmr">2,</span><span class="ML__cmr">3,</span><span class="ML__cmr">…</span></span></span></span></span>,&nbsp;the operators <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;+&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">+</span></span></span></span></span>, <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\cdot&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">⋅</span></span></span></span></span>, <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\text{^}&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__text">^</span></span></span></span></span>, <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;-&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">−</span></span></span></span></span>, and <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;/&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">/</span></span></span></span></span>, and the relations <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;=&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">=</span></span></span></span></span>, <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\neq&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__rlap"><span class="ML__inner"><span class="ML__cmr"></span></span></span><span class="ML__cmr">=</span></span></span></span></span>, <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\leq&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">≤</span></span></span></span></span>, and <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\lt&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">&lt;</span></span></span></span></span>. Exponents must be&nbsp;integers and you cannot divide by zero.&nbsp;</p>
<p>But will be inapplicable to something like this because it is not an equation and contains a variable.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;0&lt;x^2&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__cmr">0</span><span class="ML__cmr">&lt;</span><span class="ML__mathit">x</span><span class="ML__msubsup"><span class="ML__vlist-t"><span class="ML__vlist-r"><span class="ML__vlist" style="height: 0.87em;"><span style="top: -3.41em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span style="height: 0.46em; display: inline-block; font-size: 70%;"><span class="ML__cmr">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> by algebra</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">Whether allowing such a rule will allow someone to prove a contradiction by exploiting something like e.g.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;\\frac{x}{x}=1&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__mfrac"><span class="ML__vlist-t ML__vlist-t2"><span class="ML__vlist-r"><span class="ML__vlist" style="height: 0.94em;"><span class="ML__center" style="top: -2.31em;"><span style="height: 0.44em; display: inline-block;"><span class="ML__mathit">x</span></span></span><span class="ML__center" style="top: -3.5em;"><span style="height: 0.44em; display: inline-block;"><span class="ML__mathit">x</span></span></span></span><span class="ML__vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span><span class="ML__cmr">=</span><span class="ML__cmr">1</span></span></span></span></span> by algebra</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">in a proof where <span class="lurch-atom" contenteditable="false" data-metadata_type="&quot;expositorymath&quot;" data-metadata_latex="&quot;x=0&quot;"><span class="lurch-atom-body"><span class="ML__latex"><span class="ML__base"><span class="ML__mathit">x</span><span class="ML__cmr">=</span><span class="ML__cmr">0</span></span></span></span></span> is a possibility to consider when using this rule in any document or library, i.e., use at your own risk.</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: left;">&nbsp;</p>
<hr>
<p>&nbsp;</p></div>
